<DOC><DOCNO> AP890516-0125 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-89 1436EST</FILEID><FIRST>r a PM-OralRoberts     05-16 0162</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Oral Roberts,0167</SECOND><HEAD>Evangelist Says Fund Drive Goes Over Top</HEAD><DATELINE>TULSA, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Oral Roberts said Tuesday a seven-week``life-or-death'' fund drive raised the $11 million his ministryneeds to pay creditors.   The 71-year-old evangelist in March said he needed the money byOral Roberts University's graduation May 6 or creditors would startdismantling the school, the ministry and its hospital, the City ofFaith Medical Center.   Ministry officials met with creditors to seek additional time,and Roberts announced in a live broadcast Tuesday that the final$24,000 had been raised.   Ministry spokeswoman Jan Dargatz said that does not mean theevangelist's financial worries are over. Monthly contributions mustbe kept at about $3.3 million to sustain the ministry, theuniversity and the hospital, she said.   The ministry said monthly contributions declined from $5 millionto $2.7 million over the past two years. Roberts blamed ``a spiritof skepticism'' after scandals in the ministries of Jim Bakker andJimmy Swaggart.</TEXT></DOC>